question, feel free to introduce yourselves too. Yeah, sure. Are you all able to hear me?

00:13:09.039 --> 00:13:15.840
Yep, sounds good. I'm Jeffrey Sumner. I'm a data engineer at a gas pipeline company.

00:13:16.400 --> 00:13:23.359
My question was around, as you build out your team, do you plan to be focused more as a

00:13:23.359 --> 00:13:27.359
centralized data science team or more of a decentralized team within your organization?

00:13:27.919 --> 00:13:32.559
And if anyone else had any kind of comments on that as well, I was asked that question yesterday,

00:13:32.559 --> 00:13:39.119
and I really thought it depends more on maybe the culture of the company on how you handle

00:13:39.119 --> 00:13:47.280
that problem, but just curious on what others think. Thank you, Jeffrey. If I may ask,

00:13:47.280 --> 00:13:52.640
what is the difference between a centralized team and a decentralized team?

00:13:52.640 --> 00:13:58.479
My definition of it, at least, is centralized would be you have more of a data science team

00:13:58.479 --> 00:14:04.159
reporting up to a data science manager, whereas decentralized would be more along the lines of

00:14:04.159 --> 00:14:10.000
you've got a team within sales, a team within marketing, or a data science member on the

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:18.239
marketing team, the sales team, finance, whatever it may be. Yeah, that's such an interesting

00:14:18.239 --> 00:14:24.320
question. I'm not sure if I'm best equipped to answer it. I think I'll just draw from

00:14:25.280 --> 00:14:32.559
from PursueCare. We have, of course, typical departments, marketing, finance,

00:14:33.280 --> 00:14:40.880
ops, and I think it would make sense one day to have decentralized teams such that those data

00:14:40.880 --> 00:14:48.239
scientists can become subject matter experts as much as they could in those specific fields,

00:14:48.239 --> 00:14:56.000
such as finance or marketing. I think right now it makes more sense to have a centralized

00:14:56.000 --> 00:15:04.880
team given our size. We're about 70 employees strong, and we're really at the phase of just

00:15:05.679 --> 00:15:10.960
understanding this data and trying to better understand our business, our patients,

00:15:11.679 --> 00:15:19.760
but I think as we become a more mature company, our questions will probably become more

00:15:19.760 --> 00:15:24.320
complex in nature, and so having those decentralized teams in which they can

00:15:24.320 --> 00:15:30.080
once again have more face time with the subject matter experts would make sense, I think,

00:15:30.080 --> 00:15:33.679
but interested in other people's perspectives here.

00:15:34.559 --> 00:15:39.760
Prabha, I see you had your hand raised. Do you have feedback to add on this topic or another

00:15:39.760 --> 00:15:47.919
question? No, on this topic, I fully agree with what Asmae is saying here. I think it is the,

00:15:48.559 --> 00:15:52.640
it can be a little bit of organizational structure. There is no right answer here.

00:15:52.640 --> 00:15:59.679
Both are valid, but for a company that is starting out a data science team, I think

00:16:00.159 --> 00:16:08.960
a centralized setup is good because they can then develop and say grow this data science function

00:16:08.960 --> 00:16:14.559
as to how it will work in this company, set some good practices, et cetera, and when you're

00:16:14.559 --> 00:16:20.719
building a team, new hires have a place to come and learn, say, company processes, how does data

00:16:20.719 --> 00:16:25.039
science work, who are the best, and so forth. However, as this function grows,

00:16:25.119 --> 00:16:30.799
having data science teams within the marketing, within HR, within finance, et cetera, et cetera,

00:16:30.799 --> 00:16:38.000
shows a level of maturity now that these functions can exist and thrive within those functions,

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:44.719
you know, within these non-IT, non-data science organization, and continue to add value. So,

00:16:44.719 --> 00:16:51.359
I think there is no right answer, but I think if you look at the growth of the data science function,

00:16:51.440 --> 00:16:58.719
I fully agree with what Asma says, start centrally, but as you grow, data scientists need

00:16:58.719 --> 00:17:03.840
to understand the language of the finance team, language of the operations team, et cetera,

00:17:03.840 --> 00:17:09.839
and for them to be part of that organization accelerates that growth.

00:17:12.800 --> 00:17:16.400
Thank you, Prabha. I see a new question.

00:17:16.640 --> 00:17:21.040
Thank you, Prabha. I see a new buddy that you have your hand raised as well if you want to

00:17:21.040 --> 00:17:29.839
jump in on the topic. Yeah, thanks, Rachel. I was actually going to say everything that Prabhakar

00:17:29.839 --> 00:17:35.839
said, that when you're starting out, and this is something that we are currently struggling or

00:17:35.839 --> 00:17:44.800
working on within our company, that we are a fairly new, small, four, five people,

00:17:45.199 --> 00:17:50.560
data science team within one project. So, we are trying to hire more people, keep it more

00:17:50.560 --> 00:17:57.839
centralized, but at the same time, we've recently put out a posting for a job in a different team,

00:17:57.839 --> 00:18:04.719
because we also want to expand our work beyond our team, because our teams are segregated based

00:18:04.719 --> 00:18:09.680
on the line of work rather than just departments. So, we work on public health, but we want to do

00:18:09.680 --> 00:18:15.199
a lot more data science work in economic growth or climate change. So, we've convinced at least

00:18:15.199 --> 00:18:22.400
our economic growth team to hire one data scientist. And the way, I think, early on,

00:18:22.400 --> 00:18:27.520
having it centralized is also very important, because there is no mentorship or guidance

00:18:27.520 --> 00:18:31.599
available from those other teams. So, that's extremely important, like Prabhakar said,

00:18:32.400 --> 00:18:42.719
to develop good practices and, you know, just organization by practices. But we are also trying

00:18:42.719 --> 00:18:49.439
to, even with decentralized, if we convince more teams to hire data scientists, to keep it more,

00:18:50.400 --> 00:18:56.880
this bits of it centralized by organizing a technical working group around it, where we need

00:18:56.959 --> 00:19:02.880
and try to standardize practices or really standard training modules.

00:19:04.880 --> 00:19:06.400
Great point. Thank you.

00:19:06.400 --> 00:19:12.400
I think there is a happy middle, right? Once you, once you, you know, an organization has achieved

00:19:12.400 --> 00:19:21.359
this, a decentralized model. In my company, you know, the finance organization is set up

00:19:21.359 --> 00:19:27.920
in a centralized-decentralized, it exists in both ways. And I work in the supply chain

00:19:27.920 --> 00:19:33.599
department of my company. We have a finance lead for the supply chain organization.

00:19:34.479 --> 00:19:39.599
But that person, if you look at his reporting structure, he reports into the finance organization.

00:19:39.599 --> 00:19:45.439
So, he brings that finance expertise to the supply chain organization, but his manager,

00:19:45.760 --> 00:19:51.680
but his manager, he rolls up into the CFO organization, right? So, he continues to have,

00:19:53.119 --> 00:19:58.800
like, input from both places. He knows about supply chain, but he also follows all the best

00:19:58.800 --> 00:20:06.400
practices of finance within my company. So, there is a, you know, if a data science team has grown

00:20:06.400 --> 00:20:14.239
in maturity to have enough people to live and do data science for finance and HR, etc., you don't

00:20:14.239 --> 00:20:17.599
have to cut off the connection to the centralized data science team. That can still exist.

00:20:21.839 --> 00:20:26.800
Jill, I see you just asked a great question right now in the chat as well. Is it okay

