acronym is, but SMART goals is things that you've achieved over the course of one year. And one of

01:11:45.839 --> 01:11:52.240
those SMART goals has to be the demonstration of your professional development. And that could look

01:11:53.040 --> 01:12:01.600
differently for people. And so having, yes, exactly, specific, measurable, achievable,

01:12:01.600 --> 01:12:06.799
relevant, and time bound. And because of that, because it's literally part of my SMART goals,

01:12:06.799 --> 01:12:13.279
and that justifies time that I set aside for my professional development. And

01:12:13.520 --> 01:12:22.319
yeah, and it doesn't have to be coding. Professional development could be literally

01:12:22.319 --> 01:12:33.120
reading, I don't know, papers on plant science. Oftentimes, inspiration and the learning of new

01:12:33.120 --> 01:12:39.040
techniques and new frameworks could come from fields that could look very different from the

01:12:39.040 --> 01:12:45.359
field that you're working in currently. So I think having sort of leadership that understands

01:12:45.359 --> 01:12:52.640
that, and that accommodates that, and that embeds it in your performance is really great.

01:12:53.839 --> 01:13:02.160
And so with that, I told Nick, I wanted to TA a data science class Fridays from 10 to 1pm. And

01:13:02.160 --> 01:13:05.919
you know, I didn't really need to convince him of that. He's like, okay, yeah, that makes sense,

01:13:05.919 --> 01:13:11.439
because you're going to learn from your students. And you're going to learn, you know, about how to

01:13:11.439 --> 01:13:16.879
communicate, you know, things to people that don't have experience with doing that. And that's a

01:13:18.080 --> 01:13:22.879
big skill to have, because you'll be, I think, as a data scientist, often interfacing with people

01:13:23.520 --> 01:13:28.319
that don't understand it, and that you'll need to explain it. So yeah.

01:13:28.879 --> 01:13:32.080
I love that. You're TAing that class, too. That's awesome.

01:13:35.439 --> 01:13:40.080
I want to try and get to everyone's questions, too, but I know some people had to drop. So if

01:13:40.080 --> 01:13:44.640
you're on, and there's a question that we didn't get to yet, feel free to raise your hand and

01:13:44.640 --> 01:13:45.839
ask that live, too.

01:13:51.040 --> 01:13:55.439
One of the questions from earlier, Asma, was, I know we talked about

01:13:56.080 --> 01:14:03.600
how you have three data engineers, and then data scientists. And if that's all under your team, as

01:14:03.600 --> 01:14:12.879
well, like, do you manage the data engineering side? And the question was, is your area of expertise

01:14:12.879 --> 01:14:17.520
also in data engineering? If not, how do you go about managing that role?

01:14:18.319 --> 01:14:25.520
Right. It's definitely not part of my skill set, but I'm learning, you know, slowly but surely

01:14:25.520 --> 01:14:32.080
through them, you know, good practices and so forth. So I think I'm, like, a pseudo, really

01:14:32.080 --> 01:14:40.560
pseudo data architect in that way. So, you know, I sort of interface with the vendors in terms of

01:14:40.879 --> 01:14:47.040
interface with the vendors in terms of negotiating, you know, data access and how to obtain that data.

01:14:47.040 --> 01:14:51.759
And then I go back to my data engineers and tell them, okay, this is what the data looks like. This

01:14:51.759 --> 01:14:56.399
is, you know, the cleaning that needs to be done. This is how we should format it such that it makes

01:14:56.399 --> 01:15:03.200
it easier to, you know, slice and dice the data whenever we need to. And so that's how I've

01:15:03.200 --> 01:15:07.839
managed this team is sort of, you know, give them an understanding of the business,

01:15:07.839 --> 01:15:15.279
which then informs how the data should ideally be structured to meet those business needs.

01:15:18.720 --> 01:15:25.359
But yeah, I certainly don't really have intimate experience of data engineering. I have some ideas,

01:15:26.080 --> 01:15:32.720
but it's definitely them almost managing me in a sense. So it's a good two-way street there.

01:15:33.600 --> 01:15:39.680
Definitely. I see one other question from Yuri that we didn't ask. And I know we're quite over,

01:15:39.680 --> 01:15:45.200
so we'll start to wrap up in a few minutes here. But the question was, how much of data science

01:15:45.200 --> 01:15:49.600
is data exploration versus machine learning versus deep learning?

01:15:50.640 --> 01:16:00.160
Yeah. So I really think it depends on the company and the team and so forth. I can tell you,

01:16:01.120 --> 01:16:06.000
PursuitCare machine learning right now occupies zero of our time just because we're just literally

01:16:06.000 --> 01:16:12.720
not there yet. But it's something that, you know, once our data warehouse is mature and we've

01:16:12.720 --> 01:16:20.319
understood the basics about our business, then for sure that will become a bigger part of our time.

01:16:22.479 --> 01:16:24.479
Can I elaborate on the question?

01:16:25.120 --> 01:16:27.279
Yes, definitely. Sorry, I didn't know you were still there.

01:16:28.000 --> 01:16:36.160
Yeah. So when I try to learn this material and I feel before going into machine learning,

01:16:36.160 --> 01:16:43.040
which feels much more complex, I try to do the data science part without it. So

01:16:43.040 --> 01:16:51.279
I wonder how you study these layers of complications. Am I clear?

01:16:51.279 --> 01:17:00.959
I think so. You know, I think having exposure to machine learning is important,

01:17:00.959 --> 01:17:06.479
especially if you can fit it into your day, because there will be a time in which you're

01:17:06.479 --> 01:17:11.520
probably going to have a question that involves you, you know, modeling and maybe drawing

01:17:12.399 --> 01:17:18.640
from a machine learning model. But yeah, I think it's kind of the things like learn to,

01:17:18.640 --> 01:17:22.959
what's the expression, learn to walk before you run type of thing. I think getting really good

01:17:22.959 --> 01:17:33.759
at using group buy and summarize will make your stakeholders very, very happy. So I think if I

01:17:33.759 --> 01:17:40.560
were to give advice on someone kind of starting out, I'd focus on getting really good at, you

01:17:40.560 --> 01:17:46.319
know, being able to slice and dice the data and represent it in efficient ways before, you know,

01:17:47.200 --> 01:17:54.160
moving on to more fancier and more complex questions. Thank you. Yeah.

01:17:56.560 --> 01:18:03.279
Thank you all so much for joining and staying on past the hour too. I really appreciate you

01:18:03.279 --> 01:18:07.600
jumping on here, Asma, and sharing all your insights and experience with us too.

01:18:08.479 --> 01:18:13.200
What's the best way for people to get in contact with you if they had follow up questions?

01:18:13.759 --> 01:18:20.879
God, this is so fun. I could literally do this for hours, but we all have jobs to go to. Yeah,

01:18:20.879 --> 01:18:29.359
I think the best way is Twitter. I'm usually very active on there and will definitely respond. So

01:18:30.080 --> 01:18:35.919
thanks. I'm known as Jeep Wrangler owner. It's yes, it is my cow.

